<chapter xml:id="chapter-improper-int" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Improper integrals</title>

<section xml:id="section-improper-int-unbounded-domains">
<title>Integrals on unbounded domains</title>

<p>
Is it possible to attach a number to the <q>area</q> of the region bounded between the graph of <m>f(t) = 1/t^2</m> and the horizontal axis from <m>t = 1</m> onwards?
Or is the area simply infinite because the domain being considered is unbounded?
</p>

<figure>
	<caption>An unbounded area under the graph of <m>f(t) = 1/t^2</m>.</caption>
	<image width="56.1%">
		<shortdescription>A graph illustrating an unbounded area under the graph of the reciprocal square function.</shortdescription>
		<!-- TODO description -->
		<latex-image label="image-improper-int-area-under-recip-square">
			<xi:include href="improper-int.d/area-under-recip-square.tex" parse="text" />
		</latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
As usual in calculus,
our strategy is to approximate in a systematic way and then look for a trend in these approximations.
Here we do not want to approximate with a Riemann sum because that would require adding up the areas of an infinite number of rectangles.
Such a strategy might be feasible after we study <term>infinite series</term> in <xref ref="chapter-series" />,
but there is a simpler approach:
we simply compute <em>some</em> of the area over a <em>bounded</em> domain <m>1 \le t \le b</m>,
then compute <em>some more</em> of the area over a <em>larger</em> bounded domain
(that is, over <m>1 \le t \le b</m> for a larger value of <m>b</m>),
and so on,
and look for a trend in these partial areas.
</p>

<figure>
	<caption>An bounded partial area under the graph of <m>f(t) = 1/t^2</m>.</caption>
	<image width="56.1%">
		<shortdescription>A graph illustrating a bounded partial area under the graph of the reciprocal square function.</shortdescription>
		<!-- TODO description -->
		<latex-image label="image-improper-int-partial-area-under-recip-square">
			<xi:include href="improper-int.d/partial-area-under-recip-square.tex" parse="text" />
		</latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
However,
we will take a more <term>continuous</term> approach compared to the step-by-step approach described in the previous paragraph.
As usual, we can consider the domain endpoint as a variable,
and then the partial area values can all be collected together as an <em>integral function</em>:
<me> \text{Total area } \approx A(t) = \ccmint{1}{t}{\frac{1}{u^2}}{u} </me>.
A larger value of <m>t</m> will account for more of the area over the full, unbounded domain <m>t \ge 1</m>,
and so should be a better approximation.
Is there any trend to these increasingly better approximations?
That is,
what is the long-term behaviour of the function <m>A(t)</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>?
</p>

<p>
To investigate further,
it would be nice to have a different expression for <m>A(t)</m>,
one that better fits our previous strategies for investigating long-term behaviour.
Using <xref ref="pattern-poly-int-power-all-exp" text="type-local">Formula</xref> from <xref ref="pattern-poly-int-power" />,
we have
<md>
	<mrow> A(t) \amp = \ccmint{1}{t}{u^{-2}}{u} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = \frac{t^{-1} - 1}{-1} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = 1 - \frac{1}{t} </mrow>
</md>
But <m>1/t \to 0</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>,
so <me> \lim_{t \to \infty} A(t) = 1 </me>,
and it seems reasonable to say that the area of the region bounded between the graph of <m>f(t) = 1/t^2</m> and the horizontal axis from <m>t = 1</m> onwards is equal to <m>1</m>.
</p>

<definition>
	<title>Improper integrals on unbounded domains</title>
	<statement><p><ol>

		<li>
			For a given boundary value <m>a</m>,
			if <m>f</m> is integrable on every domain <m>a \le t \le b</m>,
			then write
			<me> \ccmint{a}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} </me>
			to represent the value of
			<me> \lim_{t \to \infty} \ccmint{a}{t}{f(u)}{u} </me>,
			if it exists.
		</li>

		<li>
			For a given boundary value <m>b</m>,
			if <m>f</m> is integrable on every domain <m>a \le t \le b</m>,
			then write
			<me> \ccmint{-\infty}{b}{f(t)}{t} </me>
			to represent the value of
			<me> \lim_{t \to -\infty} \ccmint{t}{b}{f(u)}{u} </me>,
			if it exists.
		</li>

		<li>
			Write <me> \ccmint{-\infty}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} </me> to represent the value of
			<me> \ccmint{-\infty}{0}{f(t)}{t} + \ccmint{0}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} </me>,
			if it exists.
		</li>

	</ol></p></statement>
</definition>

<remark><p>
	In the definition of the <q>two-sided</q> improper integral over the whole real number line,
	any <q>break</q> value can be used in place of <m>0</m>.
	If both <md><mrow> \amp \ccmint{-\infty}{0}{f(t)}{t} \amp \amp \ccmint{0}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} </mrow></md>
	can be computed,
	then it should be possible to compute both <md><mrow> \amp \ccmint{-\infty}{a}{f(t)}{t} \amp \amp \ccmint{a}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} </mrow></md>
	for every value of <m>a</m>,
	and it should always be the case that the sum of each of these pairs of integrals will be the same value as the sum of any other such pair of integrals.
</p></remark>

<example xml:id="example-improper-int-first-examples"><p><ol>

	<li xml:id="example-improper-int-first-examples-one-over-squared">
		<m>\displaystyle \ccmint{1}{\infty}{\frac{1}{t^2}}{t} = 1</m>,
		as already computed above.
	</li>

	<li xml:id="example-improper-int-first-examples-backward-exp-decay">
		For <m>\displaystyle \ccmint{-\infty}{0}{e^t}{t}</m> we compute
		<md>
			<mrow> \ccmint{-\infty}{0}{e^t}{t} \amp = \lim_{t \to -\infty} \ccmint{t}{0}{e^u}{u} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = - \lim_{t \to -\infty} \ccmint{0}{t}{e^u}{u} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = - \lim_{t \to -\infty} e^t - 1 </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = - (0 - 1) </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = 1 </mrow>
		</md>
	</li>

	<li xml:id="example-improper-int-first-examples-two-sided">

		<p> Consider <m>\displaystyle \ccmint{-\infty}{\infty}{t e^{-t^2}}{t} </m>. </p>

		<image width="43.5%">
			<shortdescription>A graph illustrating unbounded area under a graph in both directions.</shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image label="image-improper-int-two-sided-exp">
				<xi:include href="improper-int.d/two-sided-exp.tex" parse="text" />
			</latex-image>
		</image>

		<p> The graph of this function displays odd symmetry, so we expect the <q>two-sided</q> improper integral to compute to <m>0</m>. </p>

		<p>
		We'll first use substitution to compute an antiderivative that we can use to compute both <q>halves</q> of this improper integral.
		Using
		<md><mrow> u \amp = -t^2 \amp \dudt \amp = -2 t </mrow></md>,
		we have
		<md>
			<mrow> \ccmiint{t e^{-t^2}}{t} \amp = -\frac{1}{2} \ccmiint{e^{-t^2} (-2 t)}{t} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = -\frac{1}{2} \ccmiint{e^{-t^2} \cdot \dudt}{t} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = -\frac{1}{2} \ccmiint{e^u}{u} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = -\frac{1}{2} \cdot e^u + C  </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = -\frac{1}{2} \cdot e^{-t^2} + C  </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = -\frac{1}{2 e^{t^2}} + C  </mrow>
		</md>.
		Now we'll use the specific antiderivative where <m>C = 0</m> in <xref ref="pattern-fund-thm-def-int-by-antideriv" /> when computing the two <q>halves</q>:
		<md>
			<mrow>
				\amp \ccmint{-\infty}{0}{t e^{-t^2}}{t}
				\amp
				\amp \ccmint{0}{\infty}{t e^{-t^2}}{t}
			</mrow>
			<mrow>
				\amp = \lim_{t \to -\infty} \ccmint{t}{0}{u e^{-u^2}}{u}
				\amp
				\amp = \lim_{t \to \infty} \ccmint{0}{t}{u e^{-u^2}}{u}
			</mrow>
			<mrow>
				\amp = \lim_{t \to -\infty} -\frac{1}{2 e^{0^2}} - \left(-\frac{1}{2 e^{t^2}}\right)
				\amp
				\amp = \lim_{t \to \infty} -\frac{1}{2 e^{t^2}} - \left(-\frac{1}{2 e^{0^2}}\right)
			</mrow>
			<mrow>
				\amp = \lim_{t \to -\infty} -\frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{2 e^{t^2}}
				\amp
				\amp = \lim_{t \to \infty} -\frac{1}{2 e^{t^2}} + \frac{1}{2}
			</mrow>
			<mrow>
				\amp = -\frac{1}{2} + 0
				\amp
				\amp = 0 + \frac{1}{2}
			</mrow>
			<mrow>
				\amp = -\frac{1}{2} \text{,}
				\amp
				\amp = \frac{1}{2} \text{.}
			</mrow>
		</md>
		Finally, compute
		<md>
			<mrow> \ccmint{-\infty}{\infty}{t e^{-t^2}}{t} \amp = \ccmint{-\infty}{0}{t e^{-t^2}}{t} + \ccmint{0}{\infty}{t e^{-t^2}}{t} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = -\frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{2} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = 0 </mrow>
		</md>.
		</p>

	</li>

</ol></p></example>

<p>
It's important when computing a <q>two-sided</q> improper integral to compute the two <q>halves</q> independently.
One might wonder why we need to split
<me> \ccmint{-\infty}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} = \ccmint{-\infty}{0}{f(t)}{t} + \ccmint{0}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} </me>
at all <mdash />
if improper integrals are computed a bit at a time and taking a limit,
why can't we directly compute
<me> \ccmint{-\infty}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} </me>
as <me> \lim_{t \to \infty} \ccmint{-t}{t}{f(u)}{u} </me>?
</p>

<example>

	<p>
	It is tempting to say that
	<md><mrow tag="star" xml:id="equation-improper-int-two-sided-line"> \ccmint{-\infty}{\infty}{t}{t} </mrow></md>
	should be equal to zero because,
	just like the last example in <xref ref="example-improper-int-first-examples" />,
	the function being integrated exhibits odd symmetry,
	and the negative area over domain <m>t \le 0</m> should <q>cancel</q> with the positive area over domain <m>t \ge 0</m>.
	</p>

	<image width="35.0%">
		<shortdescription>A graph illustrating unbounded area under a graph in both directions for a linear function.</shortdescription>
		<!-- TODO description -->
		<latex-image label="image-improper-int-two-sided-linear">
			<xi:include href="improper-int.d/two-sided-linear.tex" parse="text" />
		</latex-image>
	</image>

	<p>
	This is exactly what happens if we compute
	<me> \lim_{t \to \infty} \ccmint{-t}{t}{u}{u} = \lim_{t \to \infty} 0 = 0 </me>.
	However, the cancellation of negative area with positive area only works over bounded domains.
	We have
	<md><mrow tag="dstar" xml:id="equation-improper-int-one-sided-lines">
		\ccmint{-\infty}{0}{t}{t} \amp = -\infty \amp \ccmint{0}{\infty}{t}{t} \amp = \infty
	</mrow></md>,
	and we have no conceptual basis we can use to justify cancelling a negatively-oriented area of infinite magnitude with a positively-oriented area of infinite magnitude.
	Instead,
	it's best to say that <xref ref="equation-improper-int-two-sided-line" /> <term>diverges</term> because the two integrals in <xref ref="equation-improper-int-one-sided-lines" /> do.
	</p>

</example>

<definition>
	<title>Convergence/divergence of improper integrals</title>
	<statement><p>
		If the limit defining an improper integral exists,
		then we say the improper integral <term>converges</term>,
		otherwise we say it <term>diverges</term>.
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<example xml:id="example-improper-int-one-over"><p>
	While the integral of <m>f(t) = 1/t^2</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m> converges,
	the integral of <m>g(t) = 1/t</m> does not:
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\ccmint{1}{\infty}{\frac{1}{t}}{t}
			\amp = \lim_{t \to \infty} \ccmint{1}{t}{\frac{1}{u}}{u}
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \lim_{t \to \infty} \ln(t) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \infty </mrow>
	</md>.
</p></example>

<p> It turns out that <m>t^{-1}</m> is the <q>cusp</q> between convergence and divergence for power functions. </p>

<fact xml:id="fact-improper-int-p-funcs">
	<title>Convergence of improper integrals for (reciprocal) power functions</title>

	<statement><p>
		The improper integral <me> \ccmint{1}{\infty}{\frac{1}{t^p}}{t} </me> converges for <m>p \gt 1</m> and diverges for <m>p \le 1</m>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof><p>
		The case of <m>p = 1</m> produces a divergent integral,
		as already verified in <xref ref="example-improper-int-one-over" />.
		For <m>p \neq 1</m>,
		we have
		<md>
			<mrow> \ccmint{1}{\infty}{\frac{1}{t^p}}{t} \amp = \lim_{t \to \infty} \ccmint{1}{t}{\frac{1}{u^p}}{u} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \lim_{t \to \infty} \frac{t^{-p + 1} - 1}{-p + 1} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{1 - p} \left( \lim_{t \to \infty} t^{1 - p} - 1 \right) </mrow>
		</md>.
		Whether this limit exists depends on whether the exponent on <m>t</m> is negative or positive.
		If <m>p \gt 1</m> then the exponent is negative and <m>t^{1 - p} \to 0</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>,
		so that <me> \ccmint{1}{\infty}{\frac{1}{t^p}}{t} = \frac{1}{p - 1} </me>.
		If <m>p \lt 1</m> then the exponent is positive and <m>t^{1 - p} \to \infty</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>,
		and the limit doesn't exist.
	</p></proof>

</fact>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-improper-int-properties">
<title>Properties</title>

<p>
The following records the fact that if we are able to integrate as <m>t \to \infty</m> (or as <m>t \to -\infty</m>),
then we should be able to do so from any starting point.
</p>

<fact xml:id="fact-improper-int-converge-restart">

	<statement><p>
		If one of the integrals
		<md><mrow> \amp \ccmint{a_1}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} \amp \amp \ccmint{a_2}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} </mrow></md>
		converges,
		then they both do
		(as long as we remain within the domain of integrability of <m>f(t)</m>),
		with
		<me> \ccmint{a_1}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} = \ccmint{a_1}{a_2}{f(t)}{t} + \ccmint{a_2}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} </me>.
		And similarly for improper integrals on domains <m>-\infty \lt t \le b_1</m> and <m>-\infty \lt t \le b_2</m>,
		with <me> \ccmint{-\infty}{b_2}{f(t)}{t} = \ccmint{-\infty}{b_1}{f(t)}{t} + \ccmint{b_1}{b_2}{f(t)}{t} </me>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof><p>
		Suppose <m>a_1 \lt a_2</m>.
		Then
		<md>
			<mrow> \ccmint{a_1}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} \amp = \lim_{t \to \infty} \ccmint{a_1}{t}{f(u)}{u} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \lim_{t \to \infty} \left( \ccmint{a_1}{a_2}{f(u)}{u} + \ccmint{a_2}{t}{f(u)}{u} \right) </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \ccmint{a_1}{a_2}{f(u)}{u} + \lim_{t \to \infty} \ccmint{a_2}{t}{f(u)}{u} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \ccmint{a_1}{a_2}{f(t)}{t} + \ccmint{a_2}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} </mrow>
		</md>.
		Since the integral over domain <m>a_1 \le t \le a_2</m> is just a number,
		the two integrals must both converge or both diverge.
	</p></proof>

</fact>

<p>
Note that the relationships between improper integrals with different starting/ending points in <xref ref="fact-improper-int-converge-restart" /> agrees with the pattern in <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props-split" text="type-local">Property</xref> of <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props" />.
Here are some other familiar patterns from <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props" />.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-improper-int-linearity">
	<title>Linearity of improper integrals</title>

	<statement><p>
		<ol>

			<li>
				If <m>\displaystyle \ccmint{a}{\infty}{f(t)}{t}</m> converges,
				then so does <m>\displaystyle \ccmint{a}{\infty}{k f(t)}{t}</m>,
				and <me> \ccmint{a}{\infty}{k f(t)} = k \ccmint{a}{\infty}{f(t)} </me>.
			</li>

			<li>
				If both <md><mrow> \amp \ccmint{a}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} \amp \amp \ccmint{a}{\infty}{g(t)}{t} </mrow></md> converge,
				then so does <m>\displaystyle \ccmint{a}{\infty}{f(t) + g(t)}{t}</m>,
				and <me> \ccmint{a}{\infty}{f(t) + g(t)}{t} = \ccmint{a}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} + \ccmint{a}{\infty}{g(t)}{t} </me>.
			</li>

		</ol>
		And similar facts hold for the other types of improper integrals.
	</p></statement>

	<proof><p>
		These follow from the limit definition of improper integrals,
		and the <xref ref="pattern-func-limits-laws" text="title" />.
	</p></proof>

</identity>

<p>
Finally,
it should be clear that the only way that an improper integral can converge is if the height of the area is decreasing to zero.
</p>

<fact xml:id="fact-improper-int-converges-implies-h-asymp-at-0"><p><ol>
	<li>
		If an improper integral of <m>f(t)</m> converges as <m>t \to \infty</m>,
		then it must be that <m>f(t) \to 0</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
	</li>
	<li>
		If an improper integral of <m>f(t)</m> converges as <m>t \to -\infty</m>,
		then it must be that <m>f(t) \to 0</m> as <m>t \to -\infty</m>.
	</li>
</ol></p></fact>

<warning><p>
	Do not get <xref ref="fact-improper-int-converges-implies-h-asymp-at-0" /> backwards!
	<xref ref="example-improper-int-one-over" /> demonstrates that knowing <m>f(t) \to 0</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m> is <alert>not</alert> sufficient for an improper integral to converge as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
</p></warning>

<p> The contrapositive of <xref ref="fact-improper-int-converges-implies-h-asymp-at-0" /> is often useful to avoid unnecessary work. </p>

<corollary xml:id="corollary-improper-int-diverges-if-not-h-asymp-at-0"><p><ol>
	<li>
		If <m>f(t) \not\to 0</m> as <m>t \to \infty</m>,
		then the improper integral of <m>f(t)</m> must diverge as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
	</li>
	<li>
		If <m>f(t) \not\to 0</m> as <m>t \to -\infty</m>,
		then the improper integral of <m>f(t)</m> must diverge as <m>t \to -\infty</m>.
	</li>
</ol></p></corollary>

<example><p>
	The improper integral <me> \ccmint{2}{\infty}{\frac{2 t^3 - 3 t + 1}{t^3 + t^2 - 5}}{t} </me> must diverge because
	<me> \frac{2 t^3 - 3 t + 1}{t^3 + t^2 - 5} \to 2 \qquad\text{as}\qquad t \to \infty </me>.
</p></example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-improper-int-comparison">
<title>Comparison tests</title>

<introduction>

	<p>
	While <xref ref="fact-improper-int-converges-implies-h-asymp-at-0" /> says that we need <m>f(t) \to 0</m>as <m>t \to \infty</m> for an improper integral to converge as <m>t \to \infty</m>,
	if <m>f(t)</m> is too <em>slow</em> to converge to <m>0</m>,
	then the integral will not converge.
	This is precisely what is happening with the two integrals
	<md><mrow> \amp \ccmint{1}{\infty}{\frac{1}{t}}{t} \text{,} \amp \amp \ccmint{1}{\infty}{\frac{1}{t^2}}{t} \text{.} </mrow></md>
	The function <m>f(t) = 1/t</m> converges to zero as <m>t \to \infty</m>,
	but it does so too slowly and so the accumulating area grows too quickly for it to converge to a specific value.
	But the square in <m>g(t) = 1/t^2</m> allows this function to converge to zero more quickly,
	limiting the growth of the area as <m>t \to \infty</m> and allowing trend of partial areas to stay bounded.
	</p>

	<p>
	Now consider <me> \ccmint{0}{\infty}{e^{-t^2}}{t} </me>.
	We saw that an improper integral of exponential decay converges in <xref ref="example-improper-int-first-examples-backward-exp-decay" text="type-local">Integral</xref> of <xref ref="example-improper-int-first-examples" />,
	which is not surprising because exponential decay decays very quickly.
	And this integral squares <m>t</m> before inputting it into exponential decay,
	so it decays even faster.
	Because of this,
	we should expect this integral to converge.
	But how could we be sure?
	The function <m>f(t) = e^{-t^2}</m> is (famously) an example of a function where is it impossible to write down an antiderivative without using an integral
	(that is, using the <xref ref="theorem-fund-thm" text="title" />).
	</p>

	<p>
	The comparison tests in this section allow us to determine convergence without actually computing the integral value,
	by comparing the integral to one whose convergence is already known.
	</p>

	<note><p>
		In this section,
		we will only concern ourselves with integrals where <m>t \to \infty</m>,
		but similar facts/patterns hold for integrals where <m>t \to -\infty</m>.
	</p></note>

</introduction>

<subsection>
<title>Comparing areas</title>

<p>
If one improper integral converges,
and the partial areas of a second improper integral are all smaller in magnitude than those of the first,
than it stands to reason that the second improper integral should converge as well.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-improper-int-compare">
	<title>Comparison test for integrals</title>

	<statement><p>
		Assume <m> 0 \le f(t) \le g(t)</m> for <m>t \ge a</m>.
		<ol>
			<li> If <m>\displaystyle \ccmint{a}{\infty}{g(t)}{t}</m> converges then so does <m>\displaystyle \ccmint{a}{\infty}{f(t)}{t}</m>. </li>
			<li> If <m>\displaystyle \ccmint{a}{\infty}{f(t)}{t}</m> diverges then so does <m>\displaystyle \ccmint{a}{\infty}{g(t)}{t}</m>. </li>
		</ol>
	</p></statement>

</identity>

<figure>
	<caption>An illustration of <xref ref="pattern-improper-int-compare" />.</caption>
	<image width="49.4%">
		<shortdescription>A graph depicting comparison of two improper integrals.</shortdescription>
		<!-- TODO description -->
		<latex-image label="image-improper-int-compare">
			<xi:include href="improper-int.d/compare.tex" parse="text" />
		</latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<proof>
	<title>Idea of justification</title>

	<p>
	Since <m> 0 \le f(t) \le g(t)</m>,
	the partial area functions
	<md><mrow>
		F(t) \amp = \ccmint{a}{t}{f(u)}{u} \amp
		G(t) \amp = \ccmint{a}{t}{g(u)}{u}
	</mrow></md>
	are non-decreasing and also satisfy <m> 0 \le F(t) \le G(t)</m> for <m>t \ge a</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	If the improper integral of <m>g</m> converges,
	then <m>G(t)</m> must be bounded,
	hence <m>F(t)</m> must be bounded as well.
	Since <m>F(t)</m> is non-decreasing,
	it must converge as <m>t \to \infty</m>
	(<xref ref="theorem-seq-monotonic-conv" text="title" />).
	Hence the improper integral of <m>f</m> converges as well.
	</p>

	<p>
	On the other hand,
	suppose we start with the assumption that the improper integral of <m>f</m> diverges.
	As the partial area function <m>F(t)</m> is non-decreasing,
	we can conclude that it is unbounded.
	Since <m>G(t) \ge F(t)</m> for <m>t \ge a</m>,
	<m>G(t)</m> must be unbounded as well,
	in which case the improper integral of <m>g</m> diverges as well.
	</p>

</proof>

<!--
