 <example>
	<title>Convergence by comparison</title>

	<p>
	We will use the <xref ref="pattern-improper-int-compare" text="title" /> to compare the following two integrals:
	<md><mrow> \amp \ccmint{0}{\infty}{e^{-t^2}}{t} \amp \amp \ccmint{0}{\infty}{e^{-t}}{t} </mrow></md>.
	A horizontal reflection of <xref ref="example-improper-int-first-examples-backward-exp-decay" text="type-local">Integral</xref> of <xref ref="example-improper-int-first-examples" /> yields
	<me> \ccmint{0}{\infty}{e^{-t}}{t} = 1 </me>,
	hence this integral converges.
	For the comparison,
	first consider that exponential values are always positive.
	Further more,
	for <m>t \ge 1</m> we have <m>t^2 \ge t</m>,
	and so <m>e^{t^2}</m> will be further out on the exponential growth graph than <m>e^t</m>.
	Thus,
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow> e^{t^2} \ge e^t </mrow>
		<mrow> \frac{1}{e^{t^2}} \le \frac{1}{e^t} </mrow>
		<mrow> 0 \lt e^{-t^2} \le e^{-t} </mrow>
	</md>
	as required by the <xref ref="pattern-improper-int-compare" text="title" />.
	From this we conclude
	<ul>
		<li>
			Because <m>\displaystyle \ccmint{0}{\infty}{e^{-t}}{t}</m> converges,
			so does <m>\displaystyle \ccmint{1}{\infty}{e^{-t}}{t}</m>.
			(<xref ref="fact-improper-int-converge-restart" />)
		</li>
		<li>
			By comparison with <m>\displaystyle \ccmint{1}{\infty}{e^{-t}}{t}</m>,
			<m>\displaystyle \ccmint{1}{\infty}{e^{-t^2}}{t}</m> converges
			(<xref ref="pattern-improper-int-compare" />)
		</li>
		<li>
			Because <m>\displaystyle \ccmint{1}{\infty}{e^{-t^2}}{t}</m> converges,
			so does <m>\displaystyle \ccmint{0}{\infty}{e^{-t^2}}{t}</m>.
			(<xref ref="fact-improper-int-converge-restart" />)
		</li>
	</ul>
	If we wanted some idea of the value of the improper integral of <m>e^{-t^2}</m>,
	we could approximate it numerically with partial integrals.
	The Sage cell below will allow you to do that by increasing the upper bound of integration.
	What do you notice as you increase the upper bound <m>t</m>?
	What does this say about the graph of <m>f(t) = e^{-t^2}</m>?
	</p>

	<sage>
		<input>
			var('u')
			t = 2
			integrate(e^(-u^2),u,0,t).n()
		</input>
		<output> 0.882081390762422 </output>
	</sage>

</example>

<example><title>Divergence by comparison</title><p>
	Consider <me> \ccmint{1}{\infty}{\frac{e^t + 1}{t e^t}}{t} </me>.
	Since exponential values are always positive,
	we have
	<me> \frac{e^t + 1}{t e^t} = \frac{1}{t} + \frac{1}{t e^t} \gt \frac{1}{t} </me>
	for positive <m>t</m>.
	Therefore the integral above diverges by comparison with the improper integral of <m>1/t</m>
	(<xref ref="example-improper-int-one-over" />).
</p></example>

<p>
Sometimes an improper integral of a function that is oscillating between positive and negative values is difficult to analyze;
the following fact sometimes allows us to convert the question of convergence to one about a non-negative function.
</p>

<fact xml:id="fact-improper-int-abs-conv">
	<title>Absolute convergence of improper integrals</title>

	<statement><p>
		If an improper integral of <m>\abs{f(t)}</m> converges,
		then so will an improper integral of <m>f(t)</m>.
	</p></statement>

	<proof><p>
		Assume <me> \ccmint{a}{\infty}{\abs{f(t)}}{t} </me> converges.
		Then from <xref ref="pattern-improper-int-linearity" />,
		so do both of
		<md><mrow> \amp \ccmint{a}{\infty}{2 \abs{f(t)}}{t} \text{,} \amp \amp \ccmint{a}{\infty}{- \abs{f(t)}}{t} \text{.} </mrow></md>
		For all <m>t</m> in the domain of <m>f</m> we have
		<md alignment="gather">
			<mrow> \phantom{\implies} \quad -\abs{f(t)} \le f(t) \le \abs{f(t)} \quad \phantom{\implies} </mrow>
			<mrow> \implies \quad 0 \le f(t) + \abs{f(t)} \le 2 \abs{f(t)} \text{.} \quad \phantom{\implies} </mrow>
		</md>
		So by comparison, <me> \ccmint{a}{\infty}{f(t) + \abs{f(t)}}{t} </me> must converge.
		But then adding this convergent integral to another will yield a convergent integral
		(<xref ref="pattern-improper-int-linearity" />),
		so <me> \ccmint{a}{\infty}{\Bbrac{f(t) + \abs{f(t)} + \bbrac{-\abs{f(t)}}}}{t} = \ccmint{a}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} </me>
		converges.
	</p></proof>

</fact>

<example><p>
	Consider <me> \ccmint{0}{\infty}{e^{-t} \sin(t)}{t} </me>.
	The amplitude of the sine function in the integrand is decaying exponentially,
	so it seems like this integral should converge.
	We have <me> 0 \le \abs{\sin(t)} \le 1 \qquad \implies \qquad 0 \le \abs{e^{-t} \sin(t)} \le e^{-t}  </me>,
	and so the improper integral of <m>\abs{e^{-t} \sin(t)}</m> converges by comparison with the improper integral of <m>e^{-t}</m>.
	And then the improper integral of <m>e^{-t} \sin(t)</m> converges by <xref ref="fact-improper-int-abs-conv" />.
</p></example>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Comparing rates</title>

<p>
An improper integral converges if it accumulates area slowly enough that the area doesn't become unbounded.
But this is directly related to how quickly the height of the graph tends to <m>0</m>.
So we should be able to compare improper integrals based on how quickly the functions being integrated tend to <m>0</m>.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-improper-int-limit-compare">
	<title>Limit comparison test for integrals</title>
	<p>
	If <me>\lim_{t \to \infty} \frac{f(t)}{g(t)}</me> exists and is positive
	(that is, <m>f(t)</m> and <m>g(t)</m> grow/decay at the same rate as <m>t \to \infty</m>),
	then the two improper integrals
	<md><mrow> \amp \ccmint{a}{\infty}{f(t)}{t} \amp \amp \ccmint{a}{\infty}{g(t)}{t} </mrow></md>
	either <em>both</em> converge or <em>both</em> diverge.
	</p>
</identity>

<example><p>
	Consider <me> \ccmint{2}{\infty}{\frac{2 t^2 - 3 t + 1}{t^3 + t^2 - 5}}{t} </me>.
	For large <m>t</m>,
	considering dominant terms we have <me> \frac{2 t^2 - 3 t + 1}{t^3 + t^2 - 5} \approx \frac{2}{t} </me>,
	But comparing the two using the <xref ref="pattern-improper-int-compare" text="title" /> might be difficult.
	Instead,
	let's compare their relative rates of growth:
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\lim_{t \to \infty} \frac{(2 t^2 - 3 t + 1) / (t^3 + t^2 - 5)}{1/t} \amp
			\lim_{t \to \infty} \frac{2 t^2 - 3 t + 1}{t^3 + t^2 - 5} \cdot \frac{t}{1}
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \lim_{t \to \infty} \frac{2 t^3 - 3 t^2 + t}{t^3 + t^2 - 5} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \lim_{t \to \infty} \frac{2 \cancel{t^3}}{\cancel{t^3}} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 2 </mrow>
	</md>.
	Since these two functions decay to zero at the same rate,
	then the integrals
	<md><mrow> \amp \ccmint{2}{\infty}{\frac{2 t^2 - 3 t + 1}{t^3 + t^2 - 5}}{t} \amp \amp \ccmint{2}{\infty}{\frac{2}{t}}{t} </mrow></md>
	either both converge or both diverge.
	But we know that the second integral diverges by combining
	<xref ref="example-improper-int-one-over" /> and <xref ref="pattern-improper-int-linearity" />,
	and therefore so does the first integral.
</p></example>

</subsection>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-improper-int-near-asymptotes">
<title>Integrals near a vertical asymptote</title>

<p>
We can think of vertical asymptotes as <q>inverses</q> of horizontal asymptotes.
If we can sometimes attach a number to the area squeezed between a graph and a horizontal asymptote at <m>y = 0</m>,
we should be able to sometimes attach a number to the area squeezed between a graph and a vertical asymptote.
To compute such an improper integral,
we take a limit as one of the boundaries approaches the location of the vertical asymptote.
</p>

<definition>
	<title>Improper integrals near a vertical asymptote</title>
	<statement><p>
		Suppose the graph of <m>f(t)</m> has a vertical asymptote at <m>t = c</m>,
		and that <m>a \lt c \lt b</m>.
		Then we define
		<ol>
			<li><m> \ccmint{a}{c}{f(t)}{t} = \lim_{t \to c^{-}} \ccmint{a}{t}{f(u)}{u} </m></li>
			<li><m> \ccmint{c}{b}{f(t)}{t} = \lim_{t \to c^{+}} \ccmint{t}{b}{f(u)}{u} </m></li>
			<li><m> \ccmint{a}{b}{f(t)}{t} = \ccmint{a}{c}{f(t)}{t} + \ccmint{c}{b}{f(t)}{t} \text{.} </m></li>
		</ol>
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<figure>
	<caption>
		Improper integrals near a vertical asymptote,
		from left and from right.
	</caption>

	<sidebyside widths="44.4% 44.4%">

		<figure>
			<caption>
				A left-handed improper integral at a vertical asymptote.
				The partial area <m>\ccmint{a}{t}{f(u)}{u}</m> approximates the total area <m>\ccmint{a}{c}{f(t)}{t}</m>.
			</caption>
			<image>
				<shortdescription>A graph depicting a left-handed improper integral at a vertical asymptote.</shortdescription>
				<!-- TODO description -->
				<latex-image label="image-improper-int-vert-asymptote-left">
					<xi:include href="improper-int.d/vert-asymptote-left.tex" parse="text" />
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<figure>
			<caption>
				A right-handed improper integral at a vertical asymptote.
				The partial area <m>\ccmint{t}{b}{f(u)}{u}</m> approximates the total area <m>\ccmint{c}{b}{f(t)}{t}</m>.
			</caption>
			<image>
				<shortdescription>A graph depicting a right-handed improper integral at a vertical asymptote.</shortdescription>
				<!-- TODO description -->
				<latex-image label="image-improper-int-vert-asymptote-right">
					<xi:include href="improper-int.d/vert-asymptote-right.tex" parse="text" />
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

	</sidebyside>

</figure>

<example><p>
	Let's try various (reciprocal) power functions near the asymptote at <m>t = 0</m>.
	<ol>
		<li>
			First we'll try <m>f(t) = 1/t</m>.
			<md>
				<mrow> \ccmint{0}{1}{\frac{1}{t}}{t} \amp = \lim_{t \to 0^{+}} \ccmint{t}{1}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \lim_{t \to 0^{+}} - \ccmint{1}{t}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \lim_{t \to 0^{+}} - \ln(t) </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \infty </mrow>
			</md>
			The divergence of this integral should not be a surprise:
			the function is self-inverse
			(that is, <m>\inv{f}(t) = f(t)</m>)
			and so its graph is symmetric about the line <m>y = t</m>.
			Thus the accumulation of area as <m>t \to 0^{+}</m> should mirror the accumulation of area as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
		</li>

		<li>
			Now let's try <m>g(t) = 1/t^2</m>.
			<md>
				<mrow> \ccmint{0}{1}{\frac{1}{t^2}}{t} \amp = \lim_{t \to 0^{+}} \ccmint{t}{1}{\frac{1}{u^2}}{u} </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \lim_{t \to 0^{+}} - \ccmint{1}{t}{u^{-2}}{u} </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \lim_{t \to 0^{+}} - \left( \frac{t^{-1} - 1}{-1} \right) </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \lim_{t \to 0^{+}} \frac{1}{t} - 1  </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \infty </mrow>
			</md>
			It might be a surprise that this integral also diverges,
			since the integral of <m>g</m> <em>converges</em> as <m>t \to \infty</m>.
			But this function's graph is <em>not</em> symmetric about the line <m>y = t</m>,
			so the two improper integrals (as <m>t \to 0^{+}</m> versus as <m>t \to \infty</m>)
			are not related.
			In fact,
			<m>\inv{g}(t) = 1/\sqrt{t}</m>,
			the integral of which diverges as <m>t \to \infty</m>
			(see <xref ref="fact-improper-int-p-funcs" />),
			which coincides with the divergence of the integral of <m>g</m> as <m>t \to 0^{+}</m>.
		</li>

		<li>
			Based on the previous example,
			we might have better luck with <m>h(t) = 1/sqrt{t}</m>.
			<md>
				<mrow> \ccmint{0}{1}{\frac{1}{\sqrt{t}}}{t} \amp = \lim_{t \to 0^{+}} \ccmint{t}{1}{\frac{1}{\sqrt{u}}}{u} </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \lim_{t \to 0^{+}} - \ccmint{1}{t}{u^{-1/2}}{u} </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \lim_{t \to 0^{+}} - \left( \frac{t^{1/2} - 1}{1/2} \right) </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \lim_{t \to 0^{+}} 2 (1 - \sqrt{t})  </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 2  </mrow>
			</md>
		</li>

	</ol>
</p></example>

<p>
A function with a non-zero horizontal asymptote will not have a convergent integral as <m>t \to \infty</m>,
because the area bounded between the asymptote and the horizontal axis will be infinite.
That is,
if we take a function whose integral converges as <m>t \to \infty</m>,
(which necessarily means the function has a horizontal asymptote at <m>y = 0</m>,
see <xref ref="fact-improper-int-converges-implies-h-asymp-at-0" />),
we cannot shift that function up or down without causing the integral of the shifted function to diverge as <m>t \to \infty</m>
(see <xref ref="corollary-improper-int-diverges-if-not-h-asymp-at-0" />).
In contrast,
we <em>can</em> shift vertical asymptotes around without affecting convergence of improper integrals near that asymptote.
</p>

<example><p>
	The function <m>f(t) = 1/\sqrt{t - 2}</m> is a shift to the right of a previous example we have computed,
	and has a vertical asymptote at <m>t = 2</m>.
	Let's verify that the shifted integral converges as well:
	<me> \ccmint{2}{3}{\frac{1}{\sqrt{t - 2}}}{t} </me>.
	First,
	we'll compute <me> \ccmint{t}{3}{\frac{1}{\sqrt{u - 2}}}{u} </me>,
	assuming <m>t \gt 2</m>.
	For integrand <m>f(u) = 1/\sqrt{u - 2}</m> we can simply guess an antiderivative <m>F(u) = 2 \sqrt{u - 2}</m> and apply
	<xref ref="pattern-fund-thm-def-int-by-antideriv" />:
	<me> \ccmint{t}{3}{\frac{1}{\sqrt{u - 2}}}{u} = 2 \sqrt{3 - 2} - 2 \sqrt{t - 2} = 2 (1 - \sqrt{t - 2}) </me>.
	But as <m>t \to 2^{+}</m>,
	we have <m>\sqrt{t - 2} \to 0</m>,
	so we conclude that <me> \ccmint{2}{3}{\frac{1}{\sqrt{t - 2}}}{t} = 2 (1 - 0) = 2 </me>,
	as expected.
</p></example>

</section>

<!-- <xi:include href="./TODO.d/activities.ptx" />
<xi:include href="./TODO.d/exercises.ptx" /> -->

</chapter>
